column7: AI/ML, DevOps, Systems Engineering, Network Engineering, Biotech, Firmware, Hardware
column9: Networking with people already in the industry and finding people to work with.
column10: They would work at any company, whether Big Tech or a startup. They would be knowledgeable in many fields but hopefully at least full-stack. I don't care much about their background, just whether they are able to assist and connect with me.
column11: I would ask for their advice on what sectors of SWE to go into and what classes they think are helpful. I would also ask for tips for interviewing and optimizing my resume, as well as what projects to do to. I would have a discussion with them about how they advanced in their career and how I can reach a position like theirs.

column7: Backend and infrastructure engineering, with a focus on scalable systems, APIs, and data pipelines. Interested in developer platforms, reliability, and performance critical services. Enjoy building tools that support large numbers of users and enable other engineers to move faster.
column9: I need help to land a a job in big tech, plan out my classes, and weigh going to grad school.
column10: I’m looking for mentorship on navigating the path to big tech roles, including technical interview preparation and long term career positioning. I’d also value guidance on planning coursework strategically and weighing the tradeoffs between industry experience and pursuing graduate school.
column11: Meeting 1: Align on goals and background. Review my resume, coursework, and target roles. Identify gaps and set clear outcomes for the mentorship. Meeting 2: Deep dive on technical preparation. Review data structures and system design expectations for internships. Get feedback on problem solving approach and communication. Meeting 3: Career strategy. Discuss recruiting timelines, referrals, project selection, and how to position experiences for big tech. Review interview stories and decision making. Meeting 4: Long term planning. Evaluate coursework and internship choices, discuss graduate school versus industry, and define a concrete 6 to 12 month action plan.

column8: Operating systems, compilers, anything to do with hardware/memory
column10: Someone from a game development company like Blizzard, etc., expert in developing games and increasing performance
column11: Resume review, mock interviews, the mentor's experiences, recommendations/tips/tracks

column7: Frontend, Backend, Python, Java, Web Development, Cloud Computing, System Design, AI Engineering, Machine Learning, C++
column9: Resume Formatting, Interview Preparation and Performance
column10: My ideal mentor would work in Big Tech (Google, Meta, Amazon, Nvidia, etc), ML/AI companies like (Waymo, OpenAI, Anthropic), or work in FinTech like (Sofi, PayPal, JaneStreet, HRT, etc) as a software developer.
column11: Meeting 1: Develop a roadmap on what to do to set myself up for a successful career. Meeting 2: Work on resume formatting and a cover letter blueprint. Meeting 3: Work on Interview Skills. Meeting 4: Polish up anything that was missed.

column9: Getting out of college fast and smooth
column10: Someone who works in/is an expert in hardware
column11: Talking about career and school stuff

column7: something along the lines of python and java
I am interested in the software engineering aspects of computer science.
column8: I am generally disinterested in the parts of software engineering that I do not find interesting or that do not involve software development.
column9: need mentoring on how to advance my career and improve my skills. I am looking for advice on things that I do not currently know so that I can know them later. basically I want to bridge the gap between where I am now and where I will be in the future.
column10: My ideal mentor would look like a person who is a software engineer. They would work at a company that employs software engineers for money. They should be an expert in the field they are currently working in and their background should be relevant to the job they currently hold.
column11: Meeting 1: We will introduce ourselves and say hello. Meeting 2: We will meet for the second time to discuss things. Meeting 3: We will continue the discussion from the previous meeting. Meeting 4: We will conclude the mentorship program and say goodbye.
